Should these be a separate commit?
These are checked in in this commit, so I thought it made sense here;  If you'd like me to break out the fast_monotonic_timer into its own commit, I can.
anything to make this commit smaller / it sounds separate would be good but won't require it.
Will split up as this gets closer.
Is there any performance hit to doing this?
None that I can measure.
Any design or documentation for this?

Good point, need to update Redfish.md.  Not sure a design is required in this case;  Aside from schemas its a hundred or so line patchset, with schema.  If you want me to write a design doc I will, but it's largely going to be "Implement this schema"
I've updated Redfish.md.

Why enabled by default? 
This is oem. I don't think redfish-oem-manager-fan-data should be enabled by default, feel the same here.

Generally we enable everything by default if it functions.  the only reason I would consider changing the default for OEM fan data is because of its quality.  It's easy enough to disable the features that a user doesn't want.

I'd also mention that enabling all features by default is a form of advertising that they exist.  Folks that don't like things are free to disable features, that's why the option is there, but having it in the redfish tree by default, especially when it has basically no impact on performance is useful.

I feel that isn't what we have done elsewhere though and I struggle with OEM being enabled by default.

OEM client ID: 
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/commit/08bdcc71e5804db9b5c35361e8456e636d258b04
should have that been enabled by default?

Yes, it should've been enabled by default considering it was in the OpenBMC namespace, by definition, it applies to the majority of OpenBMC systems, so it should've been enabled by default.  If it were in the IBM namespace, that would've been different.

> I struggle with OEM being enabled by default.

Why?  The defaults are intended to expose all the functions, which a designer can disable at their choice.  Waaaaaay too many people ignore the code and look directly at the redfish tree, so we need to have a policy that understands that.

If this option had any measurable impact if you don't pull down the schema, I would've thought a little differently, but I don't really see a reason to not have this in the defaults.

I am still struggling a bit with this and all openbmc oem being enabled by default. 
Just like Oem client Id, do a majority of companies want this ?
I guess you are saying the only performance hit is a slight increase in binary size. In openbmc/openbmc we typically enable new features by default? E.g. when LDAP was added  it was added here: https://github.com/openbmc/openbmc/blob/ed7346e3a02e40eeb6357d466513d537897e592a/meta-phosphor/recipes-phosphor/images/obmc-phosphor-image.bb#L39

Then later companies can disable it if they choose: 
https://github.com/openbmc/openbmc/commit/374d8ae19c6261fdb46f6355fa0526163160499a

Is that still standard for openbmc/openbmc?

> Just like Oem client Id, do a majority of companies want this ?

Your point about it being OEM was well taken, but once it's not OEM, here's my thinking:
1. Every developer using it needs to debug bmcweb at some point
2. Every client accessing bmcweb will need to debug errors at some point, and enabling this by default helps them to do it.
3. There's no downside to a service exposing it.

> Is that still standard for openbmc/openbmc?

IMO, given the input we have, I don't see how we can do different at this point.  FWIW, in my configuration document, LDAP would be considered "user opt in", so there's not really any reason to not have it enabled by default, and I agree, it should be there in the defaults.  That's the same thing as this feature.  If you never access the telemetry, it has nearly zero effect, but when you need it, it's important it's there.

Admittedly, some of this is me trying to make a judgement call.
did you talk with Redfish about adding these?
I haven't, because it didn't seem like something you could interop, but it's a fair ask to at least have that discussion.  ACK.
